The United States and China recognize the interconnectedness of their economies and the importance of strong and sustainable growth. They commit to using all policy tools to foster confidence and strengthen growth. They also reaffirm their commitment to exchange rate stability and refrain from competitive devaluations. Both countries agree on the need for structural reforms, with China focusing on cutting excess capacity, reducing inventory, deleveraging, and lowering costs. The United States emphasizes the importance of domestic investment, infrastructure, education, and immigration reform. Both countries support the IMF and the World Bank, as well as efforts to address global excess capacity and enhance intellectual property protection. They also commit to promoting innovation and developing an inclusive and resilient international economic architecture. The United States and China will continue bilateral cooperation on trade and investment, aviation, and other areas of mutual interest.